2026-04-21 01:34:57 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 1 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 2 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 3 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 4 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 5 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 6 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 7 (indicator LED + series resistor)', 'Control module 8 (indicator LED + series resistor)'] hypothesis_explanation='The inspection outcome states that, in all eight control modules, the power-flow/switch-indicator LEDs and their series resistors are physically absent and not replaceable. In the given schematic these LED+resistor branches are drawn as being connected between the 12 V and 0 V rails of each control module, but they are non-essential parallel indicator branches. Their removal should not interrupt the series path from the power supply to the load; therefore, strictly speaking, they should not prevent the load lamp from turning on as long as the switches and main conductors are intact.\n\nHowever, the diagnostic description identifies these missing LED+resistor assemblies as the only confirmed physical anomaly across the modules. If in this implementation the indicator assemblies were actually realized as part of the current-carrying path (for example, their removal opened the respective 12 V conductors within each module), then the series chain would be broken at any module where the LED assembly is missing. Because the components are “not replaceable,” their absence would permanently interrupt the circuit, and the lamp would never turn on despite the power-supply LED being lit and all switches set to ON.\n\nBased on the current information and the explicit note that all indicator LED+resistor components (1–8) are missing and non-replaceable, the most plausible root cause for the lamp not operating is that these missing components in the control modules have opened the series path, so the control modules need repair/replacement to restore their internal indicator branches and continuity.'
