2026-04-21 01:35:29 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Load module internal wiring between input cables and lamp/indicator (including series diode)'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules 1–8 are proven good in series: subchain tests show that PSU→ctrl1–5→load and PSU→ctrl7–8→load each light the lamp, so every control module’s series path and the load module itself work correctly with the PSU and load **when connected via the correct cables**.\n\nHowever, when all modules 1–8 plus the load are assembled in the nominal chain, the main lamp is not lit despite a good battery and all switches ON. Earlier tracing with all modules connected showed 12 V propagating correctly to the output of control module 5 but being lost at the output of control module 6, with no polarity reversal. Later, by bypassing module 6 and testing subchains, it was confirmed that:\n- The loss of voltage is not due to an internal open in module 6 (ctrl6 works fine when part of a shorter chain).\n- The PSU is capable of supplying the load and the load works.\n\nThe only consistent explanation is a wiring/configuration fault at the **load end** when the full chain is assembled—most plausibly within the load module’s own internal connections between its incoming cable terminals, the series diode, and the parallel lamp/indicator. A mis‑termination (e.g., one of the input leads not actually bonded to the diode/lamp network, or the diode wired in series with only a subset of modules) would allow some partial configurations to work (subchains) but fail in the intended full‑chain connection.\n\nThus, the suspected faulty component is the load module’s internal wiring path from its two cable inputs through the series diode to the lamp and indicator (including the diode itself and its terminations). Fixing that wiring or replacing that internal harness/assembly should restore correct operation for all 8 control modules connected in series.'
