2026-04-21 01:35:55 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal series path (switch + conductors) of Control Module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='Voltage tracing with all modules in series showed 12 V present up to the output of Control Module 5, but lost at the positive output of Control Module 6, with no polarity inversion and with all cabling between modules confirmed correct by continuity tests. When Module 6 is bypassed, the remaining modules 1–5 and 7–8 can each form working sub‑chains that successfully light the lamp, proving that the PSU, load module (including its diode and wiring), external cabling, and the other seven control modules’ series paths are all functional. Since cross‑polarity cabling has been ruled out and all faults are resistive or open from Ctrl6 onward, the only consistent explanation is an internal open (or very high resistance) in the main series conduction path of Control Module 6 (its switch/PCB traces/terminal connections), while its indicator branch is not required for load operation. Therefore Control Module 6’s internal series path (switch plus conductors) is the root cause preventing current from reaching the load when the full chain is assembled.'
